  <static seed="1427" source="Contrib/PCC/BasicAlgebra/RationalExpressionAlgebraSkills/complexFractions11.pg">
    <statement><p>Calculate the following. Use an improper fraction in your answer.</p>
<p><ol label="a.">
<li>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\frac{ 1 }{ \frac{9}{7} } =}</m> <fillin characters="19" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
</li>
<li>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\frac{ \frac{1}{9} }{7} =}</m> <fillin characters="19" name="AnSwEr0002"/></p>
</li>
</ol></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>{\frac{7}{9}}</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>{\frac{1}{63}}</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p><ol label="a.">
<li>
<p>We multiply <m>7</m> in both the numerator and denominator:</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}
   \frac{ 1 }{ \frac{9}{7} } 
      \amp = \frac{ 1 \cdot 7 }{ \frac{9}{7} \cdot 7 } \\
      \amp = {{\frac{7}{9}}}
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
</li>
<li>
<p>We multiply <m>9</m> in both the numerator and denominator:</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}
   \frac{ \frac{1}{9} }{7} 
      \amp = \frac{ \frac{1}{9} \cdot 9 }{ 7 \cdot 9 } \\
      \amp = {{\frac{1}{63}}}
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
</li>
</ol></p>
</solution>
